bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong><em>Tara Palmeri</em></strong><strong>:=
 Back in 2017, you
wrote a </strong><strong><em>New York Times </em></strong><strong>article i=
n which you said that a lot of Trump=E2=80=99s executive orders were too mu=
ch of a reach. But in 2020, you wrote a book in which you argued that he ac=
tually didn=E2=80=99t use </strong><strong><em>enough</em></strong><strong>=
 of his presidential power. So tell me about your evolution from being conc=
erned about the way that Trump was wielding his executive power to now, whe=
re you think he can go even further.=C2=A0</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em=
>John Yoo</em>: If you put aside the political rhetoric for and against Tru=
mp, in his first term, what did he actually do in office and how did it com=
port with the way past presidents have used their own executive powers? I w=
rote that first piece, for <em>The</em> <em>New York Times</em>, when Trump=
 started out in office because I think the things he was saying he wanted t=
o do were at odds even with a very
broad understanding of the presidency. For example, he said he was going to=
 take money out of the Treasury and spend it himself on building a border w=
all. Civics 101 says that you need to get Congress to authorize funds to bu=
ild a border wall.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>So basically, if he do=
es another executive order to build a border wall, should we assume that=E2=
=80=99s just a messaging, agenda-setting memo, and there=E2=80=99s no
way he can do that unilaterally?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Yes, not with=
out money from Congress. I=E2=80=99d like to think that the second Trump te=
rm will hopefully be like the first Trump term. There will be a lot of rhet=
oric about doing things which the president can=E2=80=99t actually do. But =
then when it comes down to actually governing, Trump will try to stay withi=
n the guardrails. I covered national security, I covered law
enforcement, and I=E2=80=99d been in the Justice Department=E2=80=94that=E2=
=80=99s where Trump is talking the most about doing things. So who knows wh=
at=E2=80=99s going to happen in the second term, but the action will be at =
the point of executive orders, and how the courts will treat them.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;"><strong>If Trump comes into office with an enemies list and pas=
ses it to his D.O.J., can they investigate those people? Does he even have =
to do it by
executive order, or can he just give his team the list and tell them to go =
for it?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The idea of an enemies list worries ev=
erybody. Past presidents have had enemies lists=E2=80=94the phrase comes fr=
om <strong>Richard Nixon</strong>, who had an enemies list and gave it to t=
he I.R.S. You could say Trump is testing the limits that we=E2=80=99ve had =
on the presidency since Watergate. No, you don=E2=80=99t need an executive
order. The president is actually in charge of enforcing the law. So the hea=
d prosecutor under our Constitution is the president; the attorney general =
and every single prosecutor in the Justice Department under the Constitutio=
n is just the president=E2=80=99s assistant helping him or her enforce the =
law. So nothing stops the president from telling them to investigate people=
 on his enemies list.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The problem
for Trump, or any president, is that the courts can always stop you. So yes=
, the president can have the attorney general look into people, but for it =
to become really serious, you have to actually go to a court. You have to g=
o to a grand jury and explain why you have probable cause. There=E2=80=99s =
a limit, even on this greatest of presidential powers.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
<strong>What if he goes to one of his favorable courts, like a
lower federal court with a judge that he appointed?</strong></p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">Ultimately, you=E2=80=99re right. There are judges who give out searc=
h warrants and don=E2=80=99t even read them. You can cause people a lot of =
emotional turmoil and financial pain simply by investigating them at all. U=
ltimately, this is one of the greatest protections of our Constitution: you=
 cannot take someone=E2=80=99s liberty away without the approval of a jury.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;"><strong>What if the jury is afraid of retribution?</strong=
></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">That=E2=80=99s always possible; the jury is the last =
barrier. You could say the whole thing is biased against certain individual=
s and biased against Democrats now that Republicans are in charge. I like t=
o think our system doesn=E2=80=99t have that kind of bias; we haven=E2=80=
=99t
really seen it before in our history.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom=
:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Trump can=
 name cabinet nominees, but if they don=E2=80=99t do what he wants, he can =
remove them. But you=E2=80=99ve said in the past, in reference to when Trum=
p tried to fire Sally Yates for being =E2=80=9Cweak on borders,=E2=80=9D th=
at might be considered a misconception of the president=E2=80=99s authority=
 of removal because it was based on </strong><strong>=E2=80=9Cirrelevant ad=
 hominem
accusations.=E2=80=9D</strong><strong> Can you speak to that?</strong></p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Th=
ere=E2=80=99s a difference between the constitutional power of the presiden=
t and then the tradition and norms we follow in <em>using</em> those powers=
=2E So under the Constitution, the pres=
ident has the right to remove any cabi=
net officer=E2=80=94basically anyone down to the assistant secretary level.=
 The Supreme Court actually made this clearer than when I wrote the
<a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktx=
clJLZ0dVQmNubEs0QU9RcUNYcldRZ2Ficz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5=
jb20vMjAxNy8wMi8wNi9vcGluaW9uL2V4ZWN1dGl2ZS1wb3dlci1ydW4tYW1vay5odG1sP3V0bV=
9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGUrQmVzdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODEyJ=
TJGMjYlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVRoZStCZXN0KyUyNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0=
Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTIlMkYyMCUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9=
hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MT=
dkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoyM=
DI4NDg0fQ/81599780b5ae47c6c56af9454df813c22da1d744fc99104b199313baf6a3713f"=
 style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">article</a>. Over the p=
ast few years, they=E2=80=99ve actually been steadily broadening the power =
of the president to fire people beyond what it had been before Trump took o=
ffice. But even though presidents have had that power, they=E2=80=99ve been=
 very careful in using it. They generally have only used it to fire people =
when there=E2=80=99s a conflict over the president=E2=80=99s policy and
subordinates who didn=E2=80=99t want to follow the policy. Presidents somet=
imes want parts of their government to show independence, because then the =
public will have more faith in what=E2=80=99s happening.=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
