=2E</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">That=E2=80=99s another area where you=E2=
=80=99re going to see a lot
of presidential power. Congress has given the president a lot of power to i=
mpose unilateral tariffs and trade restrictions. Congress enacted NAFTA as =
a statute, and the president can=E2=80=99t undo a statute. But Trump hasn=
=E2=80=99t only been talking about undoing trade agreements; he=E2=80=99s b=
een talking about pulling out of NATO=E2=80=94maybe one of the most importa=
nt treaties we have.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Can he do that without
Congress?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The Supreme Court has never ruled, b=
ut the lower courts have said that presidents can break out of treaties. Bu=
t it=E2=80=99s never been done with an important treaty like NATO. Congress=
 has tried to stop him. I think they=E2=80=99ve tried to put appropriation =
riders on defense bills saying you can=E2=80=99t pull out of NATO. So that =
would spark an enormous constitutional battle. Is Trump really going to fol=
low
through on all these things he=E2=80=99s saying he=E2=80=99s going to do? T=
o pull out of NATO not only would be a fundamental change in our foreign po=
licy, but it would raise the question you=E2=80=99re asking, and it would g=
et to the Supreme Court I think for the first time: <em>Can presidents brea=
k treaties on their own?=C2=A0</em></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Trump will do this in the environment=
